{"title_page": "Kathryn D. Sullivan", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Kathryn Sullivan}}\n{{short description|American geologist and a former NASA astronaut}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox astronaut\n| image = Kathryn D. Sullivan NOAA Leadership.jpg\n| type = [[NASA]] Astronaut\n| status = Retired\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1951|10|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]], [[New Jersey]]\n| occupation = [[Geologist]] & NOAA scientist\n| current_occupation = Charles A. Lindbergh Chair of Aerospace History at the Smithsonian Institution\n| rank = {{Dodseal|USNO6|25}} [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]], [[United States Navy|USN]]\n| selection = [[List of astronauts by selection#1978|1978 NASA Group]]\n| eva1 = 1\n| eva2 = 3 hours 29 minutes\n| time = 22 days 04 hours 49 minutes\n| mission = [[STS-41-G]], [[STS-31]], [[STS-45]]\n| insignia = [[File:STS-41-G patch.png|40px]][[File:Sts31 flight insignia.png|45px]][[File:Sts-45-patch.png|40px]]\n| module = {{Infobox officeholder|embed=yes\n| office = [[Under Secretary of Commerce for Oceans and Atmosphere]]<br>10th Administrator of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]\n| term_start = March 6, 2014\n| term_end = January 20, 2017\n| term_start2 = Acting: March 1, 2013\n| term_end2 = March 6, 2014\n| president   = [[Barack Obama]]\n| predecessor = [[Jane Lubchenco]]\n| successor = [[Timothy Gallaudet]]\n| module            = \n  {{Infobox scientist | embed=yes\n  | fields            = Geology, Oceanography\n  | workplaces        = {{ublist|[[NASA]]|[[Rice University]]|[[COSI Columbus]]|[[Ohio State University]]|[[NOAA]]}}\n  | education         = \n  | alma_mater        = {{ublist|[[University of California, Santa Cruz]]|[[Dalhousie University]]}}\n  | thesis_title      = The structure and evolution of the Newfoundland Basin, offshore eastern Canada\n  | thesis_url        = https://search.proquest.com/docview/302930700\n  | thesis_year       = 1978\n  | doctoral_advisor  = [[Michael John Keen]]\n  | academic_advisors = \n  | doctoral_students = \n  | notable_students  = \n  | known_for         = \n  | influences        = \n  | influenced        = \n  | awards            = \n  }}\n}} \n}}\n'''Kathryn Dwyer Sullivan''' (born October 3, 1951) is an American [[geologist]] and a former [[NASA astronaut]]. A crew member on three [[Space Shuttle]] missions, she was the first American woman to walk in space on October 11, 1984. She was [[Under Secretary of Commerce for Oceans and Atmosphere]] and Administrator of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] after being confirmed by the U.S. Senate on March 6, 2014. Sullivan's tenure ended on January 20, 2017 with the swearing in of President [[Donald Trump]]. Following completion of her service at NOAA, she was designated as the 2017 Charles A. Lindbergh Chair of Aerospace History at the [[Smithsonian Institution]]\u2019s [[National Air and Space Museum]].,<ref name=\"airandspace.si.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/newsroom/press-releases/former-astronaut-and-noaa-administrator-kathy-d-sullivan-named-national-air|title=Former Astronaut and NOAA Administrator Kathy D. Sullivan Named National Air and Space Museum's Lindbergh Fellow|date=January 26, 2017|website=si.edu}}</ref> and has also served as a Senior Fellow at the [[Potomac Institute for Policy Studies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.potomacinstitute.org/fellows/2344-dr-kathryn-sullivan-senior-fellow|title=Dr. Kathryn Sullivan, Senior Fellow|website=www.potomacinstitute.org}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSullivan was born in [[Paterson, New Jersey]]. She is a 1969 graduate of [[William Howard Taft Charter High School (Los Angeles)|William Howard Taft High School]] in the [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles|Woodland Hills]] district of [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]. She was awarded a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Earth Sciences]] from the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] in 1973, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[Geology]] from [[Dalhousie University]] in 1978.<ref name=\"NASA JSC astronaut biography\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/sullivan-kd.html|title=Astronaut Bio: Kathryn D. Sullivan |work=nasa.gov}}</ref><ref name=\"thesis-sullivan-1978\">{{cite thesis |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/302930700/ |title=The structure and evolution of the Newfoundland Basin, offshore eastern Canada |date=1978 |publisher=[[Dalhousie University]] |type=Ph.D. |last=Sullivan |first=Kathryn Dwyer |via=[[ProQuest]] |url-access=subscription|oclc=757288717}}</ref> While at Dalhousie, she participated in several oceanographic expeditions that studied the floors of the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.<ref name=\"Kathryn Sullivan Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1309711/Kathryn-Sullivan|title=Kathryn Sullivan|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Kathryn D. Sullivan.jpg|thumb|Sullivan in her astronaut uniform]]\n\n=== Military career ===\nIn 1988, Sullivan joined the [[U.S. Naval Reserve]] as an oceanography officer, retiring with the rank of [[Captain (naval)|captain]] in 2006. She was stationed in Guam.\n\n=== NASA career ===\n[[File:Kathryn Dwyer Sullivan in 1981.ogv|thumbtime=2|thumb|left|A video of Sullivan in 1981 talking about how she felt to be selected]]\nSullivan performed the first [[extra-vehicular activity]] (EVA) by an American woman during [[Space Shuttle Challenger]] mission [[STS-41-G]] on October 11, 1984. Sullivan and mission specialist [[David Leestma]] performed a 3.5-hour space walk in which they operated a system designed to show that a [[satellite]] could be refueled in [[orbit]].<ref name=\"Kathryn Sullivan Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\"/> During their eight-day mission, the crew deployed the Earth Radiation Budget Satellite, conducted scientific observations of the earth with the OSTA-3 pallet (including the SIR-B radar, FILE, and MAPS experiments) and large format camera (LFC), conducted a [[satellite]] refueling demonstration using [[hydrazine]] fuel with the [[Orbital Refueling System]] (ORS), and conducted numerous in-cabin experiments as well as activating eight \"Getaway Special\" canisters. [[STS-41G]] completed 132 orbits of the Earth in 197.5 hours, before landing at [[Kennedy Space Center]], [[Florida]], on October 13, 1984.\n\nIn April 1990, Sullivan served on the crew of [[STS-31]], which launched from [[Kennedy Space Center]], [[Florida]], on April 24, 1990. During this five-day mission, crew members aboard the [[Space Shuttle Discovery]] deployed the [[Hubble Space Telescope]], and conducted a variety of middeck experiments involving the study of [[protein]] crystal growth, [[polymer membrane processing]], and the effects of weightlessness and magnetic fields on an [[ion arc]].<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/astros/sullivan.htm|title=Sullivan|work=astronautix.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214222235/http://astronautix.com/astros/sullivan.htm|archivedate=February 14, 2009}}</ref> They also operated a variety of cameras, including the IMAX cargo bay camera, for earth observations from their record setting altitude of 380 miles. Following 76 orbits of the earth in 121 hours, [[STS-31]] Discovery landed at [[Edwards Air Force Base]], [[California]], on April 29, 1990.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\"/>  In 1985, she became an Adjunct Professor of Geology at [[Rice University]].<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\"/>\n\nSullivan served as [[Payload Commander]] on [[STS-45]], the first [[Spacelab]] mission dedicated to [[NASA]]'s [[Mission to Planet Earth]]. During this nine-day mission, the crew operated the twelve experiments that constituted the [[ATLAS-I]] (Atmospheric Laboratory for Applications and Science) cargo.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\"/> [[ATLAS-I]] obtained a vast array of detailed measurements of atmospheric chemical and physical properties, which will contribute significantly to improving our understanding of our climate and atmosphere. In addition, this was the first time an artificial beam of [[electrons]] was used to stimulate a man-made auroral discharge.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\"/>\n\nSullivan left NASA in 1993.<ref name=\"Kathryn Sullivan Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\"/> She flew on three [[space shuttle]] missions and logged 532 hours in space.<ref name=\"NASA JSC astronaut biography\"/>\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n| [[File:STS-41-G Sullivan checks SIR-B antenna latch.jpg|thumb|Astronaut Kathryn Sullivan checks SIR-B antenna during STS-41-G]]\n| [[File:Sullivan Views the Earth - GPN-2000-001082.jpg|thumb|Astronaut Kathryn Sullivan using binoculars to view the earth during STS-41-G]]\n|}\n\n=== Civilian career ===\nAfter leaving NASA, Sullivan served as chief scientist of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA). In 1996 she was named president and CEO of the [[COSI Columbus]], an interactive science center in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. From 2006-2011 she was Director for [[Ohio State University]]'s [[Battelle Memorial Institute|Battelle]] Center for Mathematics and Science Education Policy as well as a volunteer science advisor to COSI. Under her leadership, COSI strengthened its impact on science teaching in the classroom and its national reputation as an innovator of hands-on, inquiry-based science learning resources.<ref>{{cite news |title=NASA Biographical Data|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/sullivan-kd.html|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> She was appointed to the [[National Science Board]] by President [[George W. Bush]] in 2004.\n\nIn 2009, Sullivan was elected to a three-year term as the chair of the Section on General Interest in Science and Engineering for the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].\n\nIn January 2011, the [[White House]] sent to the Senate the nomination of Sullivan by President [[Barack Obama]] to be an assistant secretary of commerce. Sullivan was first nominated in December 2010, but because the Senate did not approve her nomination and a bevy of others forwarded late in December, the White House renewed the formal requests.\n\nOn May 4, 2011, Sullivan was confirmed by unanimous consent of the [[U.S. Senate]] and appointed by President Obama to serve as Assistant Secretary of Commerce for Environmental Observation and Prediction and Deputy Administrator for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.<ref>{{cite news|title=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |url=http://www.noaanews.noaa.gov/stories2011/20110504_sullivan.html|accessdate=May 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSullivan became Acting Under Secretary of Commerce for Oceans and Atmosphere and Acting NOAA Administrator on February 28, 2013, following the resignation of [[Jane Lubchenco]].<ref name=\"Picked\">{{cite news|title=Former Astronaut Picked to Lead NOAA|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/former-astronaut-picked-to-lead-noaa/|accessdate=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPresident Obama nominated Sullivan to serve as the Under Secretary of Commerce for Oceans and Atmosphere and NOAA Administrator on August 1, 2013 and she was confirmed by the Senate on March 6, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|url=https://www.noaa.gov/kathryn-sullivan-confirmed-noaa-administrator|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Picked\"/>\n\nSullivan was named the 2017 Charles A. Lindbergh Chair of Aerospace History, a competitive 12-month fellowship at the ''[[National Air and Space Museum]]''. During her residence in the museum, Sullivan's research focused on the Hubble Space Telescope.<ref name=\"airandspace.si.edu\"/>\n\nIn November 2019, Sullivan's book [https://www.amazon.com/Handprints-Hubble-Astronauts-Invention-Innovation/dp/0262043181/ref=sr_1_1_sspa?gclid=Cj0KCQiApaXxBRDNARIsAGFdaB-tVqAeMU36abfbOE7bUuuV8PhI3J5JaxvjmZjWBUl9LEDKMWFBvNEaAj6FEALw_wcB&hvadid=326110624734&hvdev=c&hvlocphy=9031029&hvnetw=g&hvpos=1t1&hvqmt=e&hvrand=300169454959477070&hvtargid=kwd-766429363877&hydadcr=22560_9636788&keywords=handprints+on+hubble&qid=1579802031&sr=8-1-spons&psc=1&spLa=ZW5jcnlwdGVkUXVhbGlmaWVyPUExT0I4OEc3VVRCREUzJmVuY3J5cHRlZElkPUEwMzYyNTQ1MlRBMUlMUEM4UUlJSyZlbmNyeXB0ZWRBZElkPUEwMzQyNjUyS1ZWUlpGQUhJRU04JndpZGdldE5hbWU9c3BfYXRmJmFjdGlvbj1jbGlja1JlZGlyZWN0JmRvTm90TG9nQ2xpY2s9dHJ1ZQ==/ Handprints on Hubble: An Astronaut's Story of Invention] released from MIT Press. \u2018\u2019Handprints on Hubble\u2019\u2019 recounts Sullivan\u2019s experience as part of the team that launched, rescued, repaired, and maintained the Hubble Space Telescope. She discussed the book and her participation in the Hubble telescope's development and launch on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Woman's Hour]]''<ref>{{cite episode| title= Hubble astronaut Kathryn Sullivan; Romy Gill cooks spicy chickpeas; Reducing domestic violence| series= [[Woman's Hour]]| credits= Presenter: [[Jane Garvey (broadcaster)|Jane Garvey]]; Producer: Anna Lacey; Guest: Kathryn Sullivan  | network= [[BBC]]| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000fvtt  | airdate= 3 March 2020| minutes= 0:40| accessdate= 7 March 2020 }}</ref> at the [[Royal Institution]] in London in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.rigb.org/whats-on/events-2020/march/public-handprints-on-hubble| title= Handprints on Hubble| website= [[Royal Institution]]| accessdate= 7 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and other recognition==\n[[File:Kathryn D. Sullivan at BookExpo (05260).jpg|thumb|Sullivan at [[BookExpo America]] signing autographs for ''Handprints on Hubble'']]\nIn 1991, Sullivan received the Haley Space Flight Award for \"distinguished performance in the deployment of the Hubble Space Telescope on Mission STS-31 during April 1990.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics|url=https://www.aiaa.org/HonorsAndAwardsRecipientsList.aspx?awardId=1114bf4b-9ad4-488a-87e3-870d05d961f8|accessdate=January 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221000509/https://www.aiaa.org/HonorsAndAwardsRecipientsList.aspx?awardId=1114bf4b-9ad4-488a-87e3-870d05d961f8|archive-date=February 21, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Kathryn Sullivan received the Gold Medal of the [[Society of Woman Geographers]], for being the first American woman to walk in space,  during the 1984 [[Space Shuttle Challenger]] mission. She took a pennant bearing the insignia of the Society with her on that mission.<ref name=\"Medal\">{{cite web |title=SWG Gold Medalists |url=http://iswg.org/awards/past-gold-medal-recipients |website=Society of Woman Geographers |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"STS\">{{cite web |title=Pennant, Society of Woman Geographers, STS 41-G, Sullivan |url=https://airandspace.si.edu/collection-objects/pennant-society-women-geographers-sts-41-g-sullivan |website=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Sullivan was inducted into the [[Astronaut Hall of Fame]] and received the [[Adler Planetarium]] Women in Space Science Award.\n\nIn 2013, Sullivan was awarded an honorary doctorate of Science from [[Willamette University]] in conjunction with her presentation of a commencement address.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://willamette.edu/events/commencement/cla/honorary-degrees/past-recipients/2013/index.html|title=2013 Honorary Degrees|website=willamette.edu|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sullivan was honored in the [[Time 100]] list. According to [[John Glenn]], \"Kathy is not just an ivory-tower scientist. She was part of NASA's first class of female astronauts, selected in 1978, and went on to fly three shuttle missions. She is the first American woman to walk in space and served aboard the mission that deployed the [[Hubble Space Telescope]]. That role in helping humanity look outward has not prevented her from looking homeward. The planet is suffering increasingly severe upheavals, at least partly a result of climate change \u2014 [[droughts]], [[floods]], [[typhoons]], [[tornadoes]]. I believe my good friend Kathy is the right person for the right job at the right time.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The 100 Most Influential People|url=http://time.com/70882/kathryn-sullivan-2014-time-100/|accessdate=May 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Sullivan was awarded an honorary doctorate from [[Brown University]] for her \"abundant contributions to science, education and the public good, and her ongoing commitment to improving the state of our planet for future generations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.brown.edu/articles/2015/05/citations#Sullivan|title=Brown awards six honorary doctorates - News from Brown|work=brown.edu}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Sullivan presented the John H. Glenn Lecture in Space History Series at the Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum in Washington, D.C. Titled \"Looking at Earth: An Astronaut's Journey,\" Sullivan discussed her life of exploration and discovery, what it's like to fulfill her childhood dreams, and how NOAA's study of our planet helps us understand today's environmental challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/events/detail.cfm?id=17802|title=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum: John H. Glenn Lecture in Space History Series|accessdate=January 24, 2016|date=2015-07-30}}</ref>\n\nShe was elected to the National Academy of Engineering in 2017 and to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 2017.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Women in space]]\n*[[List of female astronauts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kathryn D. Sullivan}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Kathryn Sullivan}}\n*[https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/sullivan_kathryn.pdf NASA Biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jane Lubchenco]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Administrator of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|years=2014 \u2013 2017}}\n{{s-aft|after=Benjamin Friedman {{small|(acting)}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Marcia |title=BENJAMIN FRIEDMAN TO BE ACTING NOAA ADMINISTRATOR |url=http://www.spacepolicyonline.com/news/benjamin-friedman-to-be-acting-noaa-administrator |website=Space Policy Online |accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref><br>[[Timothy Gallaudet]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{AHOFONJ}}\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 8|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Ohio Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sullivan, Kathryn D.}}\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Astronaut Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:American women geologists]]\n[[Category:National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Under Secretaries of Commerce]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Dalhousie University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Cruz alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Paterson, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Scientists from California]]\n[[Category:Smithsonian Institution people]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:William Howard Taft Charter High School alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century geologists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American geologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:American astronaut-politicians]]\n[[Category:Space Shuttle program astronauts]]\n[[Category:Members of the Society of Woman Geographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American geologist and a former NASA astronaut}}\n{{Redirect|Kathryn Sullivan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox astronaut\n| image = Kathryn D. Sullivan NOAA Leadership.jpg\n| type = [[NASA]] Astronaut\n| status = Retired\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1951|10|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]], [[New Jersey]]\n| occupation = [[Geologist]] & NOAA scientist\n| current_occupation = Charles A. Lindbergh Chair of Aerospace History at the Smithsonian Institution\n| rank = {{Dodseal|USNO6|25}} [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]], [[United States Navy|USN]]\n| selection = [[List of astronauts by selection#1978|1978 NASA Group]]\n| eva1 = 1\n| eva2 = 3 hours 29 minutes\n| time = 22 days 04 hours 49 minutes\n| mission = [[STS-41-G]], [[STS-31]], [[STS-45]]\n| insignia = [[File:STS-41-G patch.png|40px]][[File:Sts31 flight insignia.png|45px]][[File:Sts-45-patch.png|40px]]\n| module = {{Infobox officeholder|embed=yes\n| office = [[Under Secretary of Commerce for Oceans and Atmosphere]]<br>10th Administrator of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]\n| term_start = March 6, 2014\n| term_end = January 20, 2017\n| term_start2 = Acting: March 1, 2013\n| term_end2 = March 6, 2014\n| president   = [[Barack Obama]]\n| predecessor = [[Jane Lubchenco]]\n| successor = [[Timothy Gallaudet]]\n| module            = \n  {{Infobox scientist | embed=yes\n  | fields            = Geology, Oceanography\n  | workplaces        = {{ublist|[[NASA]]|[[Rice University]]|[[COSI Columbus]]|[[Ohio State University]]|[[NOAA]]}}\n  | education         = \n  | alma_mater        = {{ublist|[[University of California, Santa Cruz]]|[[Dalhousie University]]}}\n  | thesis_title      = The structure and evolution of the Newfoundland Basin, offshore eastern Canada\n  | thesis_url        = https://search.proquest.com/docview/302930700\n  | thesis_year       = 1978\n  | doctoral_advisor  = [[Michael John Keen]]\n  | academic_advisors = \n  | doctoral_students = \n  | notable_students  = \n  | known_for         = \n  | influences        = \n  | influenced        = \n  | awards            = \n  }}\n}} \n}}\n'''Kathryn Dwyer Sullivan''' (born October 3, 1951) is an American [[geologist]] and a former [[NASA astronaut]]. A crew member on three [[Space Shuttle]] missions, she was the first American woman to walk in space on October 11, 1984. She was [[Under Secretary of Commerce for Oceans and Atmosphere]] and Administrator of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] after being confirmed by the U.S. Senate on March 6, 2014. Sullivan's tenure ended on January 20, 2017 with the swearing in of President [[Donald Trump]]. Following completion of her service at NOAA, she was designated as the 2017 Charles A. Lindbergh Chair of Aerospace History at the [[Smithsonian Institution]]\u2019s [[National Air and Space Museum]].,<ref name=\"airandspace.si.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/newsroom/press-releases/former-astronaut-and-noaa-administrator-kathy-d-sullivan-named-national-air|title=Former Astronaut and NOAA Administrator Kathy D. Sullivan Named National Air and Space Museum's Lindbergh Fellow|date=January 26, 2017|website=si.edu}}</ref> and has also served as a Senior Fellow at the [[Potomac Institute for Policy Studies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.potomacinstitute.org/fellows/2344-dr-kathryn-sullivan-senior-fellow|title=Dr. Kathryn Sullivan, Senior Fellow|website=www.potomacinstitute.org}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSullivan was born in [[Paterson, New Jersey]]. She is a 1969 graduate of [[William Howard Taft Charter High School (Los Angeles)|William Howard Taft High School]] in the [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles|Woodland Hills]] district of [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]. She was awarded a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Earth Sciences]] from the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] in 1973, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[Geology]] from [[Dalhousie University]] in 1978.<ref name=\"NASA JSC astronaut biography\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/sullivan-kd.html|title=Astronaut Bio: Kathryn D. Sullivan |work=nasa.gov}}</ref><ref name=\"thesis-sullivan-1978\">{{cite thesis |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/302930700/ |title=The structure and evolution of the Newfoundland Basin, offshore eastern Canada |date=1978 |publisher=[[Dalhousie University]] |type=Ph.D. |last=Sullivan |first=Kathryn Dwyer |via=[[ProQuest]] |url-access=subscription|oclc=757288717}}</ref> While at Dalhousie, she participated in several oceanographic expeditions that studied the floors of the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.<ref name=\"Kathryn Sullivan Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1309711/Kathryn-Sullivan|title=Kathryn Sullivan|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Kathryn D. Sullivan.jpg|thumb|Sullivan in her astronaut uniform]]\n\n=== Military career ===\nIn 1988, Sullivan joined the [[U.S. Naval Reserve]] as an oceanography officer, retiring with the rank of [[Captain (naval)|captain]] in 2006. She was stationed in Guam.\n\n=== NASA career ===\n[[File:Kathryn Dwyer Sullivan in 1981.ogv|thumbtime=2|thumb|left|A video of Sullivan in 1981 talking about how she felt to be selected]]\nSullivan performed the first [[extra-vehicular activity]] (EVA) by an American woman during [[Space Shuttle Challenger]] mission [[STS-41-G]] on October 11, 1984. Sullivan and mission specialist [[David Leestma]] performed a 3.5-hour space walk in which they operated a system designed to show that a [[satellite]] could be refueled in [[orbit]].<ref name=\"Kathryn Sullivan Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\"/> During their eight-day mission, the crew deployed the Earth Radiation Budget Satellite, conducted scientific observations of the earth with the OSTA-3 pallet (including the SIR-B radar, FILE, and MAPS experiments) and large format camera (LFC), conducted a [[satellite]] refueling demonstration using [[hydrazine]] fuel with the [[Orbital Refueling System]] (ORS), and conducted numerous in-cabin experiments as well as activating eight \"Getaway Special\" canisters. [[STS-41G]] completed 132 orbits of the Earth in 197.5 hours, before landing at [[Kennedy Space Center]], [[Florida]], on October 13, 1984.\n\nIn April 1990, Sullivan served on the crew of [[STS-31]], which launched from [[Kennedy Space Center]], [[Florida]], on April 24, 1990. During this five-day mission, crew members aboard the [[Space Shuttle Discovery]] deployed the [[Hubble Space Telescope]], and conducted a variety of middeck experiments involving the study of [[protein]] crystal growth, [[polymer membrane processing]], and the effects of weightlessness and magnetic fields on an [[ion arc]].<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/astros/sullivan.htm|title=Sullivan|work=astronautix.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214222235/http://astronautix.com/astros/sullivan.htm|archivedate=February 14, 2009}}</ref> They also operated a variety of cameras, including the IMAX cargo bay camera, for earth observations from their record setting altitude of 380 miles. Following 76 orbits of the earth in 121 hours, [[STS-31]] Discovery landed at [[Edwards Air Force Base]], [[California]], on April 29, 1990.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\"/>  In 1985, she became an Adjunct Professor of Geology at [[Rice University]].<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\"/>\n\nSullivan served as [[Payload Commander]] on [[STS-45]], the first [[Spacelab]] mission dedicated to [[NASA]]'s [[Mission to Planet Earth]]. During this nine-day mission, the crew operated the twelve experiments that constituted the [[ATLAS-I]] (Atmospheric Laboratory for Applications and Science) cargo.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\"/> [[ATLAS-I]] obtained a vast array of detailed measurements of atmospheric chemical and physical properties, which will contribute significantly to improving our understanding of our climate and atmosphere. In addition, this was the first time an artificial beam of [[electrons]] was used to stimulate a man-made auroral discharge.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia Astronautica\"/>\n\nSullivan left NASA in 1993.<ref name=\"Kathryn Sullivan Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\"/> She flew on three [[space shuttle]] missions and logged 532 hours in space.<ref name=\"NASA JSC astronaut biography\"/>\n{|style=\"margin: 0 auto;\"\n| [[File:STS-41-G Sullivan checks SIR-B antenna latch.jpg|thumb|Astronaut Kathryn Sullivan checks SIR-B antenna during STS-41-G]]\n| [[File:Sullivan Views the Earth - GPN-2000-001082.jpg|thumb|Astronaut Kathryn Sullivan using binoculars to view the earth during STS-41-G]]\n|}\n\n=== Civilian career ===\nAfter leaving NASA, Sullivan served as chief scientist of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA). In 1996 she was named president and CEO of the [[COSI Columbus]], an interactive science center in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. From 2006-2011 she was Director for [[Ohio State University]]'s [[Battelle Memorial Institute|Battelle]] Center for Mathematics and Science Education Policy as well as a volunteer science advisor to COSI. Under her leadership, COSI strengthened its impact on science teaching in the classroom and its national reputation as an innovator of hands-on, inquiry-based science learning resources.<ref>{{cite news |title=NASA Biographical Data|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/sullivan-kd.html|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> She was appointed to the [[National Science Board]] by President [[George W. Bush]] in 2004.\n\nIn 2009, Sullivan was elected to a three-year term as the chair of the Section on General Interest in Science and Engineering for the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].\n\nIn January 2011, the [[White House]] sent to the Senate the nomination of Sullivan by President [[Barack Obama]] to be an assistant secretary of commerce. Sullivan was first nominated in December 2010, but because the Senate did not approve her nomination and a bevy of others forwarded late in December, the White House renewed the formal requests.\n\nOn May 4, 2011, Sullivan was confirmed by unanimous consent of the [[U.S. Senate]] and appointed by President Obama to serve as Assistant Secretary of Commerce for Environmental Observation and Prediction and Deputy Administrator for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.<ref>{{cite news|title=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |url=http://www.noaanews.noaa.gov/stories2011/20110504_sullivan.html|accessdate=May 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSullivan became Acting Under Secretary of Commerce for Oceans and Atmosphere and Acting NOAA Administrator on February 28, 2013, following the resignation of [[Jane Lubchenco]].<ref name=\"Picked\">{{cite news|title=Former Astronaut Picked to Lead NOAA|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/former-astronaut-picked-to-lead-noaa/|accessdate=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPresident Obama nominated Sullivan to serve as the Under Secretary of Commerce for Oceans and Atmosphere and NOAA Administrator on August 1, 2013 and she was confirmed by the Senate on March 6, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|url=https://www.noaa.gov/kathryn-sullivan-confirmed-noaa-administrator|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Picked\"/>\n\nSullivan was named the 2017 Charles A. Lindbergh Chair of Aerospace History, a competitive 12-month fellowship at the ''[[National Air and Space Museum]]''. During her residence in the museum, Sullivan's research focused on the Hubble Space Telescope.<ref name=\"airandspace.si.edu\"/>\n\nIn November 2019, Sullivan\u2019s book [https://www.amazon.com/Handprints-Hubble-Astronauts-Invention-Innovation/dp/0262043181/ref=sr_1_1_sspa?gclid=Cj0KCQiApaXxBRDNARIsAGFdaB-tVqAeMU36abfbOE7bUuuV8PhI3J5JaxvjmZjWBUl9LEDKMWFBvNEaAj6FEALw_wcB&hvadid=326110624734&hvdev=c&hvlocphy=9031029&hvnetw=g&hvpos=1t1&hvqmt=e&hvrand=300169454959477070&hvtargid=kwd-766429363877&hydadcr=22560_9636788&keywords=handprints+on+hubble&qid=1579802031&sr=8-1-spons&psc=1&spLa=ZW5jcnlwdGVkUXVhbGlmaWVyPUExT0I4OEc3VVRCREUzJmVuY3J5cHRlZElkPUEwMzYyNTQ1MlRBMUlMUEM4UUlJSyZlbmNyeXB0ZWRBZElkPUEwMzQyNjUyS1ZWUlpGQUhJRU04JndpZGdldE5hbWU9c3BfYXRmJmFjdGlvbj1jbGlja1JlZGlyZWN0JmRvTm90TG9nQ2xpY2s9dHJ1ZQ==/ Handprints on Hubble: An Astronaut's Story of Invention] released from MIT Press. \u2018\u2019Handprints on Hubble\u2019\u2019 recounts Sullivan\u2019s experience as part of the team that launched, rescued, repaired, and maintained the Hubble Space Telescope. She discussed the book and her participation in the Hubble telescope's development and launch on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Woman's Hour]]''<ref>{{cite episode| title= Hubble astronaut Kathryn Sullivan; Romy Gill cooks spicy chickpeas; Reducing domestic violence| series= [[Woman's Hour]]| credits= Presenter: [[Jane Garvey (broadcaster)|Jane Garvey]]; Producer: Anna Lacey; Guest: Kathryn Sullivan  | network= [[BBC]]| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000fvtt  | airdate= 3 March 2020| minutes= 0:40| accessdate= 7 March 2020 }}</ref> at the [[Royal Institution]] in London in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.rigb.org/whats-on/events-2020/march/public-handprints-on-hubble| title= Handprints on Hubble| website= [[Royal Institution]]| accessdate= 7 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and other recognition==\n[[File:Kathryn D. Sullivan at BookExpo (05260).jpg|thumb|Sullivan at [[BookExpo America]] signing autographs for ''Handprints on Hubble'']]\nIn 1991, Sullivan received the Haley Space Flight Award for \"distinguished performance in the deployment of the Hubble Space Telescope on Mission STS-31 during April 1990.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics|url=https://www.aiaa.org/HonorsAndAwardsRecipientsList.aspx?awardId=1114bf4b-9ad4-488a-87e3-870d05d961f8|accessdate=January 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221000509/https://www.aiaa.org/HonorsAndAwardsRecipientsList.aspx?awardId=1114bf4b-9ad4-488a-87e3-870d05d961f8|archive-date=February 21, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Kathryn Sullivan received the Gold Medal of the [[Society of Woman Geographers]], for being the first American woman to walk in space,  during the 1984 [[Space Shuttle Challenger]] mission. She took a pennant bearing the insignia of the Society with her on that mission.<ref name=\"Medal\">{{cite web |title=SWG Gold Medalists |url=http://iswg.org/awards/past-gold-medal-recipients |website=Society of Woman Geographers |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"STS\">{{cite web |title=Pennant, Society of Woman Geographers, STS 41-G, Sullivan |url=https://airandspace.si.edu/collection-objects/pennant-society-women-geographers-sts-41-g-sullivan |website=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Sullivan was inducted into the [[Astronaut Hall of Fame]] and received the [[Adler Planetarium]] Women in Space Science Award.\n\nIn 2013, Sullivan was awarded an honorary doctorate of Science from [[Willamette University]] in conjunction with her presentation of a commencement address.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://willamette.edu/events/commencement/cla/honorary-degrees/past-recipients/2013/index.html|title=2013 Honorary Degrees|website=willamette.edu|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sullivan was honored in the [[Time 100]] list. According to [[John Glenn]], \"Kathy is not just an ivory-tower scientist. She was part of NASA's first class of female astronauts, selected in 1978, and went on to fly three shuttle missions. She is the first American woman to walk in space and served aboard the mission that deployed the [[Hubble Space Telescope]]. That role in helping humanity look outward has not prevented her from looking homeward. The planet is suffering increasingly severe upheavals, at least partly a result of climate change \u2014 [[droughts]], [[floods]], [[typhoons]], [[tornadoes]]. I believe my good friend Kathy is the right person for the right job at the right time.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The 100 Most Influential People|url=http://time.com/70882/kathryn-sullivan-2014-time-100/|accessdate=May 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Sullivan was awarded an honorary doctorate from [[Brown University]] for her \"abundant contributions to science, education and the public good, and her ongoing commitment to improving the state of our planet for future generations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.brown.edu/articles/2015/05/citations#Sullivan|title=Brown awards six honorary doctorates - News from Brown|work=brown.edu}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Sullivan presented the John H. Glenn Lecture in Space History Series at the Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum in Washington, D.C. Titled \"Looking at Earth: An Astronaut's Journey,\" Sullivan discussed her life of exploration and discovery, what it\u2019s like to fulfill her childhood dreams, and how NOAA\u2019s study of our planet helps us understand today's environmental challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/events/detail.cfm?id=17802|title=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum: John H. Glenn Lecture in Space History Series|accessdate=January 24, 2016|date=2015-07-30}}</ref>\n\nShe was elected to the National Academy of Engineering in 2017 and to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 2017.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Women in space]]\n*[[List of female astronauts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kathryn D. Sullivan}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Kathryn Sullivan}}\n*[https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/sullivan_kathryn.pdf NASA Biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jane Lubchenco]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Administrator of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|years=2014 \u2013 2017}}\n{{s-aft|after=Benjamin Friedman {{small|(acting)}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Marcia |title=BENJAMIN FRIEDMAN TO BE ACTING NOAA ADMINISTRATOR |url=http://www.spacepolicyonline.com/news/benjamin-friedman-to-be-acting-noaa-administrator |website=Space Policy Online |accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref><br>[[Timothy Gallaudet]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{AHOFONJ}}\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 8|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Ohio Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sullivan, Kathryn D.}}\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Astronaut Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:American women geologists]]\n[[Category:National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Under Secretaries of Commerce]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Dalhousie University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Cruz alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Paterson, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Columbus, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Scientists from California]]\n[[Category:Smithsonian Institution people]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:William Howard Taft Charter High School alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century geologists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American geologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:American astronaut-politicians]]\n[[Category:Space Shuttle program astronauts]]\n